[start section id="20112"]

Reviewed available outside records including the e-consult and limited radiology data.
DIAGNOSIS
#1 Distal rectal cancer
Mr. Tracy Burnett presents for evaluation and treatment of distal rectal cancer.  I had a very frank discussion with him about the need to restage, and given the progression of his symptoms, I am suspicious of T4 disease at this point.  We will start with a CT chest, abdomen, and pelvis to assess not only for the extent of pelvic disease but as well as for liver and pulmonary metastasis.  We will also obtain an MRI of the pelvis given his radicular symptoms to rule-out any nerve or spine involvement.  Endoscopic ultrasound is not felt to be helpful at this time given that previous EUS was positive for nodal disease, and we are well aware of the recommendations for preoperative chemoradiation treatment.  Colonoscopy will however be requested to assess the lesion's location, obtain biopsies for immunohistochemistry staining to rule-out Lynch syndrome, given his young age of onset, and also to rule-out synchronous neoplasm.  It is possible that the scope may not be able to be passed through this growth, and a pediatric scope may need to be considered.  MoviPrep prescription was provided.  At the conclusion of his staging studies, we will ask him to meet with Colon and Rectal Surgery.  I have discussed with the patient my suspicion that he may require a permanent colostomy at this point given the progression of the tumor down into the rectum.  We will be placing a tattoo on the distal margin of the tumor during colonoscopy.  I will hold off on a stoma nurse visit until patient has met with the Colon and Rectal surgeon to discuss surgical resection more in-depth.  Medical Oncology and Radiation Oncology consultations will be arranged for after the surgeon consultation.  We also discussed role for a rectal stent if he is obstructing; however, this would be a very distal stent and may cause a fair amount of discomfort.  Additionally, I discussed dietary measures with him given his significant weight-loss including the need for nutritional supplements as tolerated.  We discussed avoidance of constipation, and I recommended he use Colace and/or milk of magnesia.  I also prescribed Percocet one-to-two tablets every four to six hours as-needed for pain given that the Tramal he currently is using is not effective for him.  I will continue to follow-up with him throughout this process for results and further recommendations.  Patient is agreeable to immunohistochemistry staining to assess for Lynch syndrome.
I discussed with Dr. Hannah Smith.  Note to follow.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

