[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Burnett Burnett is a 38-year-old gentleman from Richmond who presents for evaluation and treatment of distal rectal cancer.  Mr. Tracy Burnett was symptomatic for several years with changes to the bowel habit and dietary intolerances.  As defecation became more difficult and bleeding commenced, he sought medical evaluation.  A colonoscopy in February 2010 was positive for a mass at 5-cm in the rectum.  Staging CT abdomen and pelvis, PET scan, and MRI were all negative for metastatic disease.  Endoscopic ultrasound suggested nodal involvement, and there was question of T4 involvement on the prostate; however, this was not obvious on CT evaluation.  CEA was 18.4 ng/mL.  Mr. Tracy Burnett then had an e-consult with Dr. Ellen Sinclair from Colon and Rectal Surgery here at HC April 12, 2010, and considering his outside evaluation, it was suggested that he proceed with neoadjuvant chemoradiation followed by surgical resection and probable coloanal anastomosis.
Unfortunately, Mr. Tracy Burnett did not pursue this treatment, and his symptoms have progressed.  He currently states he has lost 50 pounds since February, and has developed abdominal pain, perineal pain, and low-back pain, and now pain radiating down the left leg over the past ten days.  His pain is aggravated with defecation immediately, during, and after.  Use of Tramal (similar to tramadol) has not effectively managed his symptoms.  He has been utilizing milk of magnesia at bedtime to facilitate defecation.  He states he normally has a bowel movement after each meal.  Bleeding continues as well, and he also has fatigue and loss of appetite.  He has not had a recent intervention, although states that the local physician suggested a diverting ileostomy prior to undergoing chemoradiation before resection.  He presents now to Albany for evaluation and treatment.
Mr. Tracy Burnett is otherwise healthy with no chronic comorbidities include no cardiopulmonary symptoms or history.  His only previous surgery was a fixed septum of the nose in 1988.  He denies an chest pains, chest pressures, shortness-of-breath, or exertional symptoms.

